Researchers estimate the probability that a typical male friend group includes an openly gay or bisexual member is highâeven in small groups. Pew Research surveys show about 41 percent of Americans report having a close friend or family member who is gay or lesbian. That suggests that in many social circles, familiarity with LGBT individuals is increasingly common.

Social scientists and mental health experts also emphasize that disclosure rates among gay adults are strong: 77 percent of gay men say that most of their close friends know their orientation. In July 2025, a video from a Coldplay concert at Gillette Stadium in Boston went viral after the stadium kiss cam captured Andy Byron, then-CEO of data startup Astronomer, embracing Kristin Cabot, the companyâs Chief People Officer. 

The moment sparked controversy, as Byron was married at the time, and the interaction appeared to suggest an affair. Coldplay frontman Chris Martin, who noticed the couple live from the stage, joked, âEither theyâre having an affair or theyâre very shy,â fueling even more speculation and virality across TikTok, X, Reddit, and Instagram.

Astronomer quickly placed both executives on leave and launched an internal investigation. Byron resigned on July 19, followed by Cabot soon after. 

The scandal came at a critical moment for Astronomer, which had recently raised $93 million in Series D funding and was preparing for public growth. The company is known for helping teams scale Apache Airflow to run AI and data pipelines.

In a surreal twist, Astronomer responded with a satirical PR video featuring Gwyneth Paltrow â notably the ex-wife of Coldplayâs Chris Martin â acting as a temporary spokesperson. In the clip, she sarcastically deflects questions about the scandal and instead promotes Astronomerâs data platform and upcoming âBeyond Analyticsâ conference. 

The video quickly went viral again, with many calling it a âPR masterclassâ and one of the most ironic crisis management moves in recent memory.

The story has since become a case study in modern brand recovery, viral marketing, and the strange intersections of celebrity, scandal, and tech. 

It highlights how quickly a personal moment can explode into a public relations crisis â and how storytelling (even with a twist of irony) can reclaim the narrative.

Scientists created a cream that can bring hair â it cures baldness with just one week of use. 

The age-old quest for a cure for baldness may be entering a promising new chapter, thanks to groundbreaking research from UCLA scientists. 

After years of experimentation, the team has identified a moleculeâdubbed PP405âthat can successfully awaken dormant hair follicles. In early human trials, participants who applied the molecule topically at bedtime for just one week showed statistically significant results. 

Unlike many existing treatments that produce only wispy hair, PP405 is believed to stimulate the growth of full, terminal strands. 

The molecule works by inhibiting a protein that keeps follicle stem cells dormant, effectively reactivating the bodyâs natural hair-growing capabilities.

The breakthrough comes from a trio of UCLA researchers: William Lowry, Heather Christofk, and Michael Jung, who have co-founded a startup, Pelage Pharmaceuticals, to further develop and commercialize the treatment. With $16.4 million in backing from Google Ventures, the team is preparing for larger clinical trials and working toward FDA approval. While the treatment wonât work for everyone, it holds promise for the majority of individuals affected by hair loss, including those who lose hair due to aging, stress, genetics, or chemotherapy. As the researchers cautiously advance through regulatory hurdles, optimism is mounting that a reliable cure for baldness may finally be on the horizon.
